247 /**
248 This implementation of the factory method also implements flattening of
249 row constructors. Examples of flattening are:
250
251 - ROW(a, b) op ROW(x, y) => a op x P b op y.
252 - ROW(a, ROW(b, c) op ROW(x, ROW(y, z))) => a op x P b op y P c op z.
253
254 P is either AND or OR, depending on the comparison operation, and this
255 detail is left for combine().
256

258 create_scalar_predicate().
259 */

360 /*
361 We put any NOT expression into parenthesis to avoid
362 possible problems with internal view representations where
363 any '!' is converted to NOT. It may cause a problem if
364 '!' is used in an expression together with other operators
365 whose precedence is lower than the precedence of '!' yet
366 higher than the precedence of NOT.
367 */
368
369 2172 void Item_func_not::print(const THD *thd, String *str,
370 enum_query_type query_type) const {
371 2172 str->append('(');
372 2172 Item_func::print(thd, str, query_type);

2207 /**
2208 The implementation of optimized @<outer expression@> [NOT] IN @<subquery@>
2209 predicates. It applies to predicates which have gone through the IN->EXISTS
2210 transformation in in_to_exists_transformer functions; not to subquery
2211 materialization (which has no triggered conditions).
2212
2213 The implementation works as follows.
2214 For the current value of the outer expression
2215
2216 - If it contains only NULL values, the original (before rewrite by the
2217 Item_in_subselect rewrite methods) inner subquery is non-correlated and
2218 was previously executed, there is no need to re-execute it, and the
2219 previous return value is returned.
2220
2221 - If it contains NULL values, check if there is a partial match for the
2222 inner query block by evaluating it. For clarity we repeat here the
2223 transformation previously performed on the sub-query. The expression
2224
2225 <tt>
2226 ( oc_1, ..., oc_n )
2227 @<in predicate@>
2228 ( SELECT ic_1, ..., ic_n
2229 FROM @<table@>
2230 WHERE @<inner where@>
2231 )
2232 </tt>
2233
2234 was transformed into
2235
2236 <tt>
2237 ( oc_1, ..., oc_n )
2238 \@in predicate@>
2239 ( SELECT ic_1, ..., ic_n
2240 FROM @<table@>
2241 WHERE @<inner where@> AND ... ( ic_k = oc_k OR ic_k IS NULL )
2242 HAVING ... NOT ic_k IS NULL
2243 )
2244 </tt>
2245
2246 The evaluation will now proceed according to special rules set up
2247 elsewhere. These rules include:
2248
2249 - The HAVING NOT @<inner column@> IS NULL conditions added by the
2250 aforementioned rewrite methods will detect whether they evaluated (and
2251 rejected) a NULL value and if so, will cause the subquery to evaluate
2252 to NULL.
2253
2254 - The added WHERE and HAVING conditions are present only for those inner
2255 columns that correspond to outer column that are not NULL at the moment.
2256
2257 - If there is an eligible index for executing the subquery, the special
2258 access method "Full scan on NULL key" is employed which ensures that
2259 the inner query will detect if there are NULL values resulting from the
2260 inner query. This access method will quietly resort to table scan if it
2261 needs to find NULL values as well.
2262
2263 - Under these conditions, the sub-query need only be evaluated in order to
2264 find out whether it produced any rows.
2265
2266 - If it did, we know that there was a partial match since there are
2267 NULL values in the outer row expression.
2268
2269 - If it did not, the result is FALSE or UNKNOWN. If at least one of the
2270 HAVING sub-predicates rejected a NULL value corresponding to an outer
2271 non-NULL, and hence the inner query block returns UNKNOWN upon
2272 evaluation, there was a partial match and the result is UNKNOWN.
2273
2274 - If it contains no NULL values, the call is forwarded to the inner query
2275 block.
2276
2277 @see Item_in_subselect::val_bool_naked()
2278 @see Item_is_not_null_test::val_int()
2279 */

2935 various attributes of the item tree with Item_func_between as its root.

3690 are failed or NULL if ELSE item isn't defined.
3691
3692 IMPLEMENTATION
3693 In order to do correct comparisons of the CASE expression (the expression
3694 between CASE and the first WHEN) with each WHEN expression several
3695 comparators are used. One for each result type. CASE expression can be

5288 SYNOPSIS
5289 val_int()
5290
5291 DESCRIPTION
5292 Evaluate the function and return its value.
5293
5294 IMPLEMENTATION
5295 If the array object is defined then the value of the function is
5296 calculated by means of this array.
5297 Otherwise several cmp_item objects are used in order to do correct

5648 /**
5649
5650 Remove constant conditions over literals.
5651
5652 If an item is a trivial condition like a literal or an operation
5653 on literal(s), we evaluate the item and based on the result, decide
5654 if the entire condition can be replaced with an ALWAYS TRUE or
5655 ALWAYS FALSE item.
5656 For every constant condition, if the result is true, then
5657 for an OR condition we return an ALWAYS TRUE item. For an AND
5658 condition we return NULL if its not the only argument in the
5659 condition.
5660 If the result is false, for an AND condition we return
5661 an ALWAYS FALSE item and for an OR condition we return NULL if
5662 its not the only argument in the condition.
5663
5664 @param thd Current thread
5665 @param item Item which needs to be evaluated
5666 @param[out] new_item return new_item, if created
5667
5668 @return true, if error
5669 false, on success

5987 P(A or B) = P(A) + P(B) - P(A) * P(B)

 1097173 if (args[0]->type() == Item::FIELD_ITEM) {
6059 1087813 Field *const field = down_cast<Item_field *>(args[0])->field;
6060 /*
6061 Fix to replace 'NULL' dates with '0' (shreeve@uci.edu)
6062 See BUG#12594011
6063 Documentation says that
6064 SELECT datetime_notnull d FROM t1 WHERE d IS NULL
6065 shall return rows where d=='0000-00-00'
6066
6067 Thus, for DATE and DATETIME columns defined as NOT NULL,
6068 "date_notnull IS NULL" has to be modified to
6069 "date_notnull IS NULL OR date_notnull == 0" (if outer join)
6070 "date_notnull == 0" (otherwise)
6071
6072 It's a legacy convenience of the user, but it also causes problems as
6073 it's not SQL-compliant. So, to keep it confined to the above type of
6074 query only, we do not enable this behaviour when IS NULL
6075 - is internally created (it must really mean IS NULL)
6076 * IN-to-EXISTS creates IS NULL items but either they wrap Item_ref (so
6077 the if() above skips them) or are not created if not nullable.
6078 * fold_or_simplify() creates IS NULL items but not if not nullable.
6079 - is not in WHERE (e.g. is in ON)
6080 - isn't reachable from top of WHERE through a chain of AND
6081 - is IS NOT NULL (Item_func_isnotnull doesn't use this fix_fields).
6082 - is inside expressions (except the AND case above).
6083
6084 Moreover, we do this transformation at first resolution only, and
6085 permanently. Indeed, at second resolution, it's not necessary and it would
6086 even cause a problem (as we can't distinguish JOIN ON from WHERE
6087 anymore).
6088 */

6250 Filtering effect is similar to that of BETWEEN because
6251
6252 * "col like abc%" is similar to

7233 /**
7234 Get item that can be substituted for the supplied item.
7235
7236 @param field field item to get substitution field for, which must be
7237 present within the multiple equality itself.
7238
7239 @retval Found substitution item in the multiple equality.
7240
7241 @details Get the first item of multiple equality that can be substituted
7242 for the given field item. In order to make semijoin materialization strategy
7243 work correctly we can't propagate equal fields between a materialized
7244 semijoin and the outer query (or any other semijoin) unconditionally.
7245 Thus the field is returned according to the following rules:
7246

7248 first field in the multiple equality which belongs to the same semijoin
7249 is returned.
7250 2) If the given field doesn't belong to a materialized semijoin then
7251 the first field in the multiple equality is returned.
7252 */

7674 /// Extract the value from the item and append it to the output buffer
7675 /// "join_key_buffer" in a memcmp-able format.
7676 ///
7677 /// The value extracted here will be used as the key in the hash table
7678 /// structure, where comparisons between keys are based on memcmp. Thus, it is
7679 /// important that the values extracted are memcmp-able, so for string values,
7680 /// we are basically creating a sort key. Other types (DECIMAL and FLOAT(M,N)
7681 /// and DOUBLE(M, N)) may be wrapped in a typecast in order to get a memcmp-able
7682 /// format from both sides of the condition.
7683 /// See Item_func_eq::create_cast_if_needed for more details.
7684 ///
7685 /// @param thd the thread handler
7686 /// @param comparand the item we are extracting the value from
7687 /// @param comparator the comparator set up by Item_cmpfunc. This gives us the
7688 /// context in which the comparison is done. It is also needed for extracting
7689 /// the value in case of DATE/TIME/DATETIME/YEAR values in some cases
7690 /// @param is_left_argument whether or not the provided item is the left
7691 /// argument of the condition. This is needed in case the comparator has set
7692 /// up a custom function for extracting the value from the item, as there are
7693 /// two separate functions for each side of the condition
7694 /// @param max_char_length the maximum character length among the two arguments.
7695 /// This is only relevant when we have a PAD SPACE collation and the SQL mode
7696 /// PAD_CHAR_TO_FULL_LENGTH enabled, since we will have to pad the shortest
7697 /// argument to the same length as the longest argument
7698 /// @param store_full_sort_key if false, will store only a hash of string
7699 /// fields, instead of the string itself.
7700 /// @see HashJoinCondition::m_store_full_sort_key
7701 /// @param is_multi_column_key true if the hash join key has multiple columns
7702 /// (that is, the hash join condition is a conjunction)
7703 /// @param[out] join_key_buffer the output buffer where the extracted value
7704 /// is appended
7705 ///
7706 /// @returns true if a SQL NULL value was found
